WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.600
In this video, let's look at RStudio's ProToolSet and how you can use RStudio Workbench to create

00:00:12.600 --> 00:00:15.200
new JupyterLab sessions.

00:00:15.200 --> 00:00:18.920
You also have the choice of using Jupyter Notebook or VS Code with Python, but in this

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:20.719
case let's start there.

00:00:20.719 --> 00:00:25.639
We'll then publish to RStudio Connect so stakeholders can see and view and easily understand that

00:00:25.639 --> 00:00:27.320
data.

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:32.680
So let's open this new JupyterLab session and the beautiful thing about RStudio Workbench

00:00:32.680 --> 00:00:36.240
is that you can authenticate users, you can have the resources that are needed on this

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:42.000
platform and share the various resources between your collaborators.

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:47.919
So I have this example that I've already put together and so in this case we have all this

00:00:47.919 --> 00:00:53.480
data from the Center for Near-Earth Objects or asteroids and comets from NASA.

00:00:53.480 --> 00:00:58.240
And so I've got a lot of columns here, way more than I want to work with, about 40 or

00:00:58.240 --> 00:01:04.080
so, but what I want to do is just get to about 15 of those columns and understand the data

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:05.559
a bit better.

00:01:05.559 --> 00:01:11.519
So I've put together this JupyterLab notebook and in this case you can see that we've pulled

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:17.440
in some Python visualization libraries that we're going to use like Pandas, Seaborn, Plotly,

00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:22.760
Express, and we can use those to take a closer look at the data.

00:01:22.760 --> 00:01:27.000
So here we have a column list that we've just pulled in that specific data that we

00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:29.480
would like from the CSV file.

00:01:29.480 --> 00:01:33.879
Using Pandas we're reading that CSV.

00:01:33.879 --> 00:01:38.099
And then we have our column list above which we're pulling in here.

00:01:38.099 --> 00:01:41.540
So to make it a little easier to understand the data I've renamed my columns.

00:01:41.540 --> 00:01:46.480
You can, you know, of course just use the columns that come existing, but in this case

00:01:46.480 --> 00:01:51.239
we're displaying the first five rows to get a quick view of that.

00:01:51.239 --> 00:01:55.459
And I've also broken my data down by asteroids and comets based on the orbit class which

00:01:55.459 --> 00:01:56.459
helps you do that.

00:01:56.459 --> 00:02:00.180
So you've broken that data up a bit with Pandas.

00:02:00.180 --> 00:02:05.199
Now using Seaborn you could start to do things like visualize that data.

00:02:05.199 --> 00:02:06.919
There's some things that we're doing to observe the data here.

00:02:06.919 --> 00:02:10.360
In this case, you know, we're using Plotly to have a more interactive visualization.

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:18.179
We can see the majority of these comets or actually, yeah, comets in particular have

00:02:18.179 --> 00:02:21.580
been discovered in the last two decades.

00:02:21.580 --> 00:02:24.380
And then going down, there's other ways we can look at the data.

00:02:24.380 --> 00:02:30.660
But the point here is that we've done a few things to plot our data and then we can, you

00:02:30.660 --> 00:02:36.500
know, describe that data sum and maybe even have some things that we embed in this document.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:42.059
Like in this case, we've got the ability to embed, you know, HTML and more visualize some

00:02:42.059 --> 00:02:43.660
things from NASA and so on.

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:45.059
But you get the basic point.

00:02:45.059 --> 00:02:47.460
You've got a data glossary here.

00:02:47.460 --> 00:02:53.380
So let's take this Jupyter Notebook now and we'll publish it directly to RStudio Connect.

00:02:53.380 --> 00:02:58.100
So to do that, you'll actually need to open a new session in RStudio Workbench.

00:02:58.100 --> 00:03:03.800
And so we have the option to have a JupyterLab session or a Jupyter Notebook session to build

00:03:03.800 --> 00:03:05.039
our notebook.

00:03:05.039 --> 00:03:11.580
But to publish it, we'll actually go to Jupyter Notebook to do this inside of RStudio Workbench.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:16.259
And once we have this session open, then we'll see that we have another option for publishing

00:03:16.259 --> 00:03:17.820
to RStudio Connect.

00:03:17.820 --> 00:03:22.619
So we'll go to that same notebook.

00:03:22.619 --> 00:03:28.839
And once this is open, and we'll give it a moment, we'll have the option to publish directly.

00:03:28.839 --> 00:03:34.100
So now we see we have this option for publishing to RStudio Connect.

00:03:34.100 --> 00:03:38.699
And the first time that we do this, we'll actually have a dialog that pops up and we'll

00:03:38.699 --> 00:03:45.960
have the need to bring in our server name, server address.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:51.960
So once we have that, and we'll also want to go back to RStudio Connect and get an API key.

00:03:51.960 --> 00:03:56.800
Okay, so once we've logged in RStudio Connect, we see in the top right corner, we've got

00:03:56.800 --> 00:03:58.639
the user login icon.

00:03:58.639 --> 00:04:00.059
Let's select that.

00:04:00.059 --> 00:04:04.979
And then you can select API keys to set up this initial key.

00:04:04.979 --> 00:04:09.080
So we're just going to set up a new key here.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:12.399
And then once we have that, we'll copy it.

00:04:12.399 --> 00:04:15.720
We can select that to copy or just select here.

00:04:16.480 --> 00:04:20.600
And then we'll close this out and go back to RStudio Workbench.

00:04:20.600 --> 00:04:24.000
We'll paste in that API key from RStudio Connect.

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:30.299
And just give this a name as test server and use the default secure connection settings.

00:04:30.299 --> 00:04:32.640
We'll add this server.

00:04:32.640 --> 00:04:35.940
Then when we publish this, we have the option to either publish a document with the source

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:40.559
code or publish a finished document only as a static notebook.

00:04:40.559 --> 00:04:44.500
In this case, we want to publish the document with the source code.

00:04:44.500 --> 00:04:48.220
And then we'll also select the files that are associated with it.

00:04:48.220 --> 00:04:52.059
So we're going to actually select the CSV file and then there was an image file for

00:04:52.059 --> 00:04:53.779
that notebook as well.

00:04:53.779 --> 00:04:59.179
Okay, so now we're going to publish using the existing requirements text file.

00:04:59.179 --> 00:05:02.220
You could also generate one if we needed to, but in this case, we already have one.

00:05:02.220 --> 00:05:06.100
So we'll publish it.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:10.859
And we'll set this as a new location.

00:05:10.859 --> 00:05:13.579
And publish.

00:05:13.660 --> 00:05:20.140
So let's take a look at this space tracker notebook that's inside of RStudio Connect.

00:05:20.140 --> 00:05:24.920
So we have this loading here with our table and our plots.

00:05:24.920 --> 00:05:30.940
And everything is functional from the HTML standpoint within RStudio Connect.

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:37.019
The great thing about this is that now we can share this actual set of data and information

00:05:37.019 --> 00:05:40.380
with end users in a way that we can control.

00:05:40.380 --> 00:05:44.540
So we could have so that anyone could log in and view this document.

00:05:44.540 --> 00:05:47.660
We may have specific users that we want to set up.

00:05:47.660 --> 00:05:53.899
So in this case, we'll set up a profile publisher to have access.

00:05:53.899 --> 00:06:00.899
And then we can set, you know, copy this URL and share that with them to use anywhere.

00:06:00.899 --> 00:06:04.339
Another thing that you can see here is that we can schedule this document.

00:06:04.339 --> 00:06:08.779
So in this case, you could set a particular time for that to run.

00:06:08.779 --> 00:06:10.739
In this case, I have a CSV file.

00:06:10.739 --> 00:06:13.500
But you could have live data that you've connected to here.

00:06:13.500 --> 00:06:16.739
And this could rerun that document at a particular time.

00:06:16.739 --> 00:06:20.339
And even send that off to them in an email and publish it to them.

00:06:20.339 --> 00:06:25.779
So this is really helpful to control that the information is current.

00:06:25.779 --> 00:06:30.779
Now the end user has full access and can easily take a look at this notebook anywhere and

00:06:30.779 --> 00:06:36.579
be able to see the particular data live and totally up to date.

00:06:39.579 --> 00:06:40.579
Wow.

00:06:40.579 --> 00:06:41.579
That's really helpful.

00:06:41.579 --> 00:06:42.579
Thanks for watching.

00:06:42.579 --> 00:06:43.579
And we'll see you next time.

00:06:43.579 --> 00:06:43.579


